\par }\pard \qj \fi-266\li266\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx266\faauto\rin0\lin266\itap0 {\fs20 3.\tab Text comprehension requires that readers integrate two sources of information: the infor\-
mation contained in the text itself (text-based information), and information that originates outside of the text (context, general knowledge, etc.). Another way of stating this distinc\-
tion is as a contrast between what the text brings to the reader vs. what the reader brings to the text. Which of the following four theories proposes
 the largest role for what readers bring to the process of text comprehension? Rank the four in order from greatest to least emphasis on reader-originating information. Justify your ordering by analyzing the relative importance of text-based vs. reader-or
iginating information according to each of the four. Include specific examples of text-based and reader-originating aspects of comprehension in each theory in your analyses. The four theories are (in alphabetical order): Clark & Gerrig\rquote 
s (1983) theory of word meanings; Graesser, Singer, and Trabasso\rquote s (1994) theory of inference in reading; Kintsch\rquote s (1988) Construction-Integration Model of text comprehension; McKoon and Ratcliff\rquote 
s (1992) theory of inference in reading.
